Lumbosacral epidural steroid injection, transforaminal approach with fluoroscopic guidance
This is a two-level procedure with each of these 2 injections occurring at the respective neural foramen.
Patient: Andrew Kim
location:teoNO
Physician: Steven M. Guanche, MD
Date of procedure: 2023-09-29
Clinical scenario: As per our office notes
Diagnosis: Lumbar Radiculitis
Anesthesia: See separate note
Injectate: A total of 6 cc consisting of 2 cc triamcinolone (40 mg/cc), 2 cc 1 % lidocaine without epinephrine & the remainder normal saline
Levels injected: Bilateral L5
Approach: Transforaminal
Comments: None
Findings: There was excellent flow of contrast noted along the spinal nerves and within the epidural space at each level.
Procedure: Vital signs were monitored pre-, post and throughout the procedure. The patient was prepped and draped in a sterile fashion in the prone position after informed consent was signed and all the patient's questions were answered including the risks, benefits, alternative treatment options and prognosis. The risks include but are not limited to infection, allergic reaction, increased pain, lack of therapeutic benefit, steroid reaction, nerve damage, paralysis, stroke, epidural hematoma, syncope, headache, respiratory or cardiac arrest, scar formation and death.
The C-arm was positioned so that an oblique view of the foramen as noted above was visualized. The soft tissues overlying the structure were infiltrated with 1-2 cc of 1% lidocaine without epinephrine.
A 22-gauge spinal needle was inserted toward the target using a trajectory view along the fluoroscopic beam. Under AP and lateral visualization the needle was advanced so it did not puncture dura. Biplanar projections were used to confirm position. Aspiration was confirmed to be negative for CSF and/or blood. A 1-2 cc volume of Omnipaque 300 was injected and flow of contrast was noted at each level. Radiographs were obtained for documentation purposes.
The injection was administered into the level noted above. The patient tolerated the procedure well and was discharged after an appropriate period of observation. If there are any complications the patient was instructed to call us. The patient is to follow-up in 2 weeks.
Steven M. Guanche, MD, FAAPMR
